    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>How I Found DuBois</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Rebecca Reichmann letter disputes Ward Connerly's May 8 Op-Ed article accusing bookstores of discriminating against black writers in marketing of their works (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Ward Connerly (''Where 'Separate but Equal' Still Rules,'' Op-Ed, May 8) engages in racial profiling himself by assuming that only African-Americans frequent what he calls the ''ghettos'' in the bookstores.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Ward Connerly (''Where 'Separate but Equal' Still Rules,'' Op-Ed, May 8) engages in racial profiling himself by assuming that only African-Americans frequent what he calls the ''ghettos'' in the bookstores.</p>
        <p>I am a white Anglo-Saxon Protestant who browses in such sections regularly. My first memorable and serendipitous discovery, when I was 14, was W. E. B. DuBois, who forever changed my understanding of race in America.</p>
        <p>REBECCA REICHMANN  San Diego, May 10, 2000</p>
      </block>
